						<summary>

						<p>On a pillar in the verandah of the Ujjivanātha temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">M.K. Parakēsarivarman (Parāntaka I) Year 34: 941 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>Records that Pirāntakaṉ Madēvaḍigaḷ, the wife of Pirāntaka Gaṇḍarādittadēvar and daughter of Maḷapperumāḷ, made a gift of ninety sheep for burning a perpetual lamp with one <hi rend="italic">uḻakku</hi> of oil to be supplied daily by the measure <hi rend="italic">śūla-uḻakku</hi> to the god Paramēśvara of Tirukaṟkuḍi in Nandipanmamaṅgalam, a brahmadēyam on the south bank (of the river Kāvēri).</p>						

						<p>Pulished in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.</hi> Vol, IV No. 543.</p>						

						</summary>
